{"id":"haines-highway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Haines Highway","revisionId":1339101678,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haines_Highway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haines_Highway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Haines Highway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haines_Highway","revisionId":1339101678,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Haines, AK","to":"Haines Junction, AK","via":["Dalton Cache–Pleasant Camp Border Crossing, AK"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Haines","state":"AK","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":39.7,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["Haines Ferry Terminal"],"lat":59.22932,"lng":-135.44143,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Dalton Cache–Pleasant Camp Border Crossing","state":"AK","kind":"town","mileFromStart":39.7,"toNextMi":108.2,"note":"Junction toward Canada–United States borderNorthern terminus of AK-7; southern terminus of Hwy 3","control":["Canada–United States borderNorthern terminus of AK-7; southern terminus of Hwy 3"],"lat":59.45047,"lng":-136.36193,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Haines Junction","state":"AK","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":147.9,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Anchorage","Fairbanks","Whitehorse"],"lat":60.75251,"lng":-137.51008,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["The route was originally a trail used by Chilkat Tlingit traders, which eventually became the Dalton Trail. It was used by some prospectors during the Klondike Gold Rush of 1898-1899; other mining kept the lower Dalton Trail active through the years following its establishment. The British Columbia provincial government converted its portion of the trail to a wagon road in 1909 when copper mining began at Copper Butte and Mt. Glave. In 1911, 30 tons of ore were shipped from the mines.","The highway was built by the U.S. Army in 1943 as an alternate route from the Pacific Ocean to the Alaska Highway, in case the White Pass and Yukon Route railway from Skagway should be blocked. The total cost of the construction was US$13 million.","In the first decades after the war, maintenance was spotty at best; the road was plagued with blizzards in winter and mudslides in summer, and for a time in the 1960s and 1970s, all vehicles traveling the highway were monitored on radio. Year-round access was not achieved until 1963.","Complaints over the condition of the road, primarily in Alaska, led to the U.S. Congress-funded Shakwak reconstruction project. This project, covering the Haines Highway and the portion of the Alaska Highway from Haines Junction to the U.S. border, began in 1976 and was mostly complete by the 1980s, but is still continuing, providing grade improvements, rerouting of dangerous sections, and paving. Responsibility for maintenance is currently shared between the Alaska and Yukon governments."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Haines","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Haines","lat":59.23388889,"lng":-135.44694444,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Haines Junction","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Haines Junction","lat":60.75361111,"lng":-137.51083333,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"Haines Highway in AK, BC, and YT\" (Map). Google Maps. Retrieved January 10, 2018.","url":"https://www.google.ca/maps/@59.9494158,-